[[File:Christ's Kirk on the Green.jpg|thumb|"Christis Kirk on the Green" in a [[Broadside (music)#Broadside ballads|broadside ballad]] version dating from the beginning of the 18th century]]
'''"Christis Kirk on the Green"''' is an anonymous [[Middle Scots]] poem in 22 stanzas, now believed to have been written around the year 1500, giving a comic account of a brawl at a country fair.  It was for many years mistakenly attributed either to [[James I of Scotland]] or to [[James V of Scotland]].  It gave rise to a whole tradition of humorous poems on similar subjects by Scottish poets down the centuries, including [[Allan Ramsay (poet)|Allan Ramsay]] and [[Robert Burns]], and is still one of the most frequently published works in Middle Scots.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jones |first=George Fenwick |date=December 1953 |title="Christis Kirk", "Peblis to the Play", and the German Peasant-Brawl |jstor=460006|journal=Publications of the Modern Language Association |volume=68 |issue=5 |page=1101 }}</ref>  "Christis Kirk on the Green" has been called one of the finest performances in 15th-century British poetry.{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|p=14}}

== Synopsis ==

The scene opens at Christ's Kirk where a dance is in full swing on the village green.  While Tom Lutar plays the music and sings, the young women flirt with their suitors.  Two of the men, Jock and Robin Ray, neither of whom has been having much luck with the girls, start to quarrel over one of them, and blows are struck.  The fight begins to spread, and threatens to become serious as bows are produced and arrows shot, but the marksmanship of all the archers is so wild that no-one is hit.  Then a general brawl develops as pitchforks, flails and laths of wood are seized, branches are torn off, and all these weapons are brought into play.  The poet turns from one character to another, and details the blows delivered and the men struck to the ground.  While the fight is still in progress the poem breaks off.

== Transmission ==

"Christis Kirk" survives in at least seven manuscripts, including the [[Bannatyne Manuscript]], the [[Maitland Manuscripts|Maitland Folio]], and one of the [[David Laing (antiquary)|Laing]] manuscripts; of these the Maitland Folio gives the best text.{{sfn|Maclaine|1996|p=155}}{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=58}}  It was printed first in 1643 in a recension similar to that given by the Laing MS, and later in 1660, 1663, 1684, 1691 (by [[Edmund Gibson]]), and in 1706 (by [[James Watson (printer)|James Watson]]).{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=58}}

== Date and authorship ==

The poet was certainly familiar with a tradition of Scots burlesque poems that included "Peblis to the Play" and the now-lost "Falkland on the Green", and he wrote for a sophisticated audience, or at least for one above the peasant level.{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|p=5}}{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=58}}  These are almost the only reliable clues to his identity.  In 1568 [[George Bannatyne]] attributed the poem to [[James I of Scotland]], but in the next century an alternative attribution to [[James V of Scotland|James V]] was made, and in the 18th and 19th centuries a war of words between literary historians failed to decide between these two candidates.{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|pp=5–6}}  At the beginning of the 19th century James Sibbald suggested [[Robert Henryson]] as a possible author, but this idea did not find favour.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Paterson |first1=James |author-link1=James Paterson (journalist) |year=1861 |title=James the Fifth, or The Gudeman of Ballangeich |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzRcAAAAcAAJ&q=%22Sibbald+conjectures%22#v=snippet&q=%22Sibbald%20conjectures%22&f=false |location=Edinburgh |publisher=William P. Nimmo |pages=125–127 |access-date=6 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |year=1968 |orig-year=1906 |editor1-last=Smith |editor1-first=G. Gregory |title=The Poems of Robert Henryson. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6LA6AAAAMAAJ&q=%22The+word+occurs+nowhere+else+but+in+Christ%27s+Kirk+on+the+Grene%22&dq=%22The+word+occurs+nowhere+else+but+in+Christ%27s+Kirk+on+the+Grene%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjb9uG3lM_RAhWEDBoKHRHwADEQ6AEIGjAA |location=New York |publisher=Johnson Reprint |page=62 |access-date=6 February 2017 }}</ref>  In 1964 Allan H. Maclaine argued for an early 15th-century date, without committing himself to James I as author,{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|p=7}} but in 1996 he acknowledged that linguistic evidence suggested a date of around 1500.  This new date, which is now widely accepted, rules out both James I and James V, and leaves "Christis Kirk" as an anonymous poem.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Glen |first1=Duncan |author-link1=Duncan Glen |year=1999 |title=Scottish Literature: A New History from 1299 to 1999 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ttlZAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22written+about+1500%22 |location=Kirkcaldy |publisher=Akros |page=17 |isbn=0861421000 |access-date=6 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Carruthers |first1=Gerard |year=2009 |title=Scottish Literature |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bktAAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22latter+most+likely%22 |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |page=38 |isbn=9780748633081 |access-date=6 February 2017 }}</ref>{{sfn|Maclaine|1996|p=10}}

== Metre ==

The stanzas are each of ten lines rhyming ABABABABCD.{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=58}}  The first eight lines alternate [[iambic tetrameter]] with [[trimeter]], the ninth is a two-syllable "[[Bob and wheel|bob]]", and the final line forms the refrain "At Christis Kirk on the green".  Much alliteration is used, which, together with the recurring rhymes, gives the verse a headlong pace, while the bob line is useful in accentuating the humour.  The combined effect is to make the poem well-suited to recitation or singing.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=Roderick |author-link1=Roderick Watson |year=2007 |title=The Literature of Scotland: The Middle Ages to the Nineteenth Century |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lFzcCwAAQBAJ&q=%22to+be+clinched%22#v=snippet&q=%22to%20be%20clinched%22&f=false |edition=2nd |location=Basingstoke |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |page=53 |isbn=033366664X |access-date=6 February 2017 }}</ref>

== Setting ==

Most modern commentators accept the tradition, first reported in print by [[William Tytler]] in 1783, that the Christ's Kirk of the poem is a ruined church in the parish of Leslie, near the village of [[Insch]] in [[Aberdeenshire]].  According to Tytler a fair was held by this church every May Day until the end of the 17th century.  In 1715 [[Allan Ramsay (poet)|Allan Ramsay]] proposed a different [[Leslie, Fife|Leslie]] in [[Fife]] as the site of the poem, and was seconded by [[John Callander]] in his 1782 edition of the poem.  However this identification is probably based simply on a confusion of place-names, and it is no longer believed to have any good evidence in its favour.{{sfn|Maclaine|1996|pp=156–157}}<ref>{{cite book |year=1782 |editor1-last=Callander |editor1-first=John |title=Two Ancient Scottish Poems: The Gaberlunzie-Man and Christ's Kirk on the Green |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sNxfAAAAcAAJ&q=%22near+Falkland%22#v=snippet&q=%22near%20Falkland%22&f=false |location=Edinburgh |publisher=J. Balfour ''et al.'' |page=99 |access-date=7 February 2017 }}</ref>  James Sibbald identified Christ's Kirk with the church of [[St Salvator's College, St Andrews|St. Salvator's College, St. Andrews]], but, as with his authorship theory, this idea has found no supporters.<ref>{{cite book |year=1824 |editor1-last=Chalmers |editor1-first=George |editor1-link=George Chalmers (antiquarian) |title=The Poetic Remains of Some of the Scotish Kings |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KNxLAAAAcAAJ&q=%22suit+his+own+system%22#v=snippet&q=%22suit%20his%20own%20system%22&f=false |location=London |publisher=John Murray |page=135 |access-date=7 February 2017 }}</ref>

== Criticism ==

Critics agree that the main virtues of the poem do not lie in subtlety of descriptive detail, nor in coherence of structure, but in a fast-paced excitement and wild comic verve that suggest comparison with [[Dutch Golden Age painting|Dutch peasant paintings]].  Vividly described scenes of grotesque and earthy incident (possibly too earthy for some modern tastes) follow one after the other in rapid succession.{{sfn|Smith|1908}}{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|pp=12, 14}}  As the literary historian [[George Gregory Smith]] wrote, "Everybody is at fever-heat: the louder the women's voices and the harder the blows, the better the fun."  This forms a striking contrast with the [[Aureation|aureate]] manner of the poet's contemporaries, the [[Scottish Chaucerians]].{{sfn|Smith|1908}}  The exigencies of rhyme-scheme and alliteration that the poet faces are very rigorous, but he meets them with such inventiveness and apparent ease that it has been called a ''tour de force'' of mastery of technique.{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|pp=12–13}}

== Legacy ==

"Christis Kirk" and a similar earlier poem, "Peblis at the Play", exercised a noticeable influence on the [[makar]] [[William Dunbar]], some of whose poems use similar metrical and stylistic techniques to achieve a fast-moving effect.  Similar traces of the two older poems can be seen in the anonymous 16th-century "[[The Tale of Ralph the Collier|Rauf Coilyear]]", "The Cursing of Sir John Rowell" and "Symmie and his Bruder".{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=14}}{{sfn|Maclain|1964|pp=15–17}}  In 1718 the poet Allan Ramsay published "Christis Kirk" together with two additional [[canto]]s of his own composition.  This work reached a 5th edition in only five years,<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id=23072|title=Ramsay Allan (1684–1758}}</ref> and so popularized the poem that few others were reprinted so many times in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fox |first1=Adam |year=2013 |chapter=Approaches to Ephemera: Scottish Broadsides, 1679–1746 |editor1-last=Murphy |editor1-first=Kevin D. |editor2-last=O'Driscoll |editor2-first=Sally |title=Studies in Ephemera: Text and Image in Eighteenth-Century Print |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eIi_Olu7nfwC&q=%22commonly+reprinted%22#v=snippet&q=%22commonly%20reprinted%22&f=false |location=Lewisburg |publisher=Bucknell University Press |page=127 |isbn=9781611484953 |access-date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>  A fourth canto followed in 1766, published in Alexander Nicol's ''Poems on Several Subjects''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pittock |first1=Murray |author-link1=Murray Pittock |year=2008 |title=Scottish and Irish Romanticism |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=elHtMC8Od6cC&q=%22canto+as+well+as%22#v=snippet&q=%22canto%20as%20well%20as%22&f=false |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=46–47 |isbn=9780199232796 |access-date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>  One result of the poem's success was the emergence of a whole subgenre of comic poems set at fairs, country dances and similar merrymakings, and narrated by detached and amused observers, in which horseplay, practical jokes and drunkenness play a prominent part, and colourful scene-painting makes 
up for thin story-lines.{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|p=4}}{{sfn|Baraniuk|2008|p=125}}  Examples include [[Robert Fergusson]]'s "Leith Races", [[James Orr (poet)|James Orr]]'s "Donegore Hill" and "The Passengers", Samuel Thomson's "The Simmer Fair" and "The Hawk and the Weasel" and [[Robert Burns]]'s "The Jolly Beggars", "The Ordination" and "The Holy Fair".
{{sfn|Baraniuk|2008|pp=125–126}}{{sfn|Orr|2009|pp=122–123}}{{sfn|Maclaine|1964|p=3}}{{sfn|Kinghorn|1970|p=13}}  The Christis Kirk tradition continued into the 20th century in such poems as [[Robert Garioch]]'s "Embro to the Ploy".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thornton |first1=R. D. |last2=Watson |first2=R. |last3=MacInnes |first3=J. |last4=Byrne |first4=M. |year=2012 |chapter=Scotland, Poetry of |editor1-last=Greene |editor1-first=Roland |editor1-link=Roland Greene |editor2-last=Cushman |editor2-first=Stephen |title=The Princeton Encyclopedia of Poetry and Poetics |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MJVlZjIe5o8C&q=Embro#v=snippet&q=Embro&f=false |edition=4th |location=Princeton |publisher=Princeton University Press |page=1274 |isbn=9780691133348 |access-date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>

